95
00:06:54,037 --> 00:06:57,337
The intersection of fear?

96
00:06:57,337 --> 00:06:58,637
According to a story I heard,

97
00:06:58,637 --> 00:07:00,737
it's said that the cause of the accidents

98
00:07:00,737 --> 00:07:02,937
is due to the collision course phenomenon.

99
00:07:02,937 --> 00:07:06,537
What's that thing called the collision course?

100
00:07:06,537 --> 00:07:09,137
The collision course phenomenon.

101
00:07:09,137 --> 00:07:11,037
It's an intersection with a clear view,

102
00:07:11,037 --> 00:07:13,537
and in broad daylight, but still accidents occur.

103
00:07:14,737 --> 00:07:19,237
When two cars head into the intersection at the same speed,

104
00:07:19,237 --> 00:07:22,237
both cars will be positioned at an angle of 45 degrees

105
00:07:22,237 --> 00:07:24,137
at all times from the front.

106
00:07:24,137 --> 00:07:27,537
In other words, the other car always look to be in the same position,

107
00:07:27,537 --> 00:07:30,237
outside your visual range.

108
00:07:30,237 --> 00:07:31,837
The vision of humans

109
00:07:31,837 --> 00:07:35,437
are broadly divided into central and peripheral vision,

110
00:07:35,437 --> 00:07:36,737
but since it is difficult

111
00:07:36,737 --> 00:07:39,937
to confirm small things using peripheral vision,

112
00:07:39,937 --> 00:07:43,337
mutually noticing the other car may be delayed,

113
00:07:43,337 --> 00:07:46,937
and both cars may enter the intersection without noticing the other,

114
00:07:46,937 --> 00:07:48,137
thus, crash into each other.

115
00:07:51,337 --> 00:07:55,537
Then, you're saying that Mr. Kurumatani's accident

116
00:07:55,537 --> 00:07:57,737
